<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-10-23">
  <title>Resources for 10/23</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Explain why the function <m>f(x) = b^x</m> has an inverse when <m>b &gt; 0</m> and <m>b \ne 1</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Know that the inverse of <m>f(x)</m> in this case is <m>f^{-1}(x) = \log_b(x)</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use the definition of the <em>logarithm functions</em> to compute <m>\log_b(x)</m> for certain values of <m>x</m> and <m>b</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Use your understanding of logarithms to solve equations involving exponential and logarithm functions.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-intro-logarithms-2">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Introduction to Logarithms (Continued from Last Class)</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video introducing <em>logarithms</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="pjZuFMfg79M" />

    <problem>
      <title>Introduction to Logarithms</title>
      <p>
        In the first three problems, compute the given quantity.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\log_3(27)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\log_2(64)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\log_{11}(121)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose <m>\log_a(x)=3</m> and <m>\log_a(y)=5</m>.
             <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Find an expression for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> in terms of <m>a</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Use what you found in (a) to compute both <m>\log_a(xy)</m> and <m>\log_a \left( \frac{x}{y} \right)</m>
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Compute <m>\log_a \left( x^6 \right)</m> and <m>\log_a(y^4)</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-logarithm-equations">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Solving Logarithm Equations</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em>solving equations with logarithms</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="t_O2hg9Za9g" />

    <problem>
      <title>Solving Logarithm Equations</title>
      <p>
        Solve the following equations/problems.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>3\log_4(x) = 18</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>5^{6x}=3</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>20 \cdot 6^{2x}-1=15</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              (Not on quiz) Use the graph of <m>y=\left( \frac12 \right)^x</m> to draw the graph of <m>y=\log_{\frac12}(x)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              (Not on quiz) Use the graph of <m>y=e^x</m> to draw the graph of <m>y=\ln(x)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </problem>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Optional Reading</title>
    <p>
      Section 3.4: pp. 184-189
    </p>
    <p>
      Here is a link for the <url href="https://activecalculus.org/prelude/sec-exp-log.html">HTML version of Section 3.4</url>.
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>